<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#F7F7F7" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post155695"></a>
	
	<font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><b>Faustis</b></font><br>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Cleric</font><br>
	<img src="avatar.php?userid=8994&dateline=1046810749" border="0" alt=""><p>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Registered: Mar 2003<br>
	Location: <br>
	Posts: 27</font></td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#F7F7F7" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial"> <b>Healing Rotations 101</b></font>
	<p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">Preface: I just posted this in my guild's cleric forums, reposting here to get a wider view.  The info here is indicitive of the way our guild runs our CHRs other's method's may vary.<br />
<br />
----------------------------------------------------------------------------<br />
<br />
I'm going to break down, to the best of my abilities, all the various elements of being in/executing a healing rotation(CH or otherwise).  I know its long, but EVERYONE needs to read this.  Anyone who wishes to  add something, or make a suggestion please do so, I will edit it in should it prove neccissary.<br />
<br />
<br />
From this point forward I will refer to the "rotation" as CHR (complete heal rotation) for my own piece of mind, the principles of a CHR pretty much apply to non-complete heal rotations as well, with adjustments being made for the spells used.<br />
<br />
<br />
CHANNEL<br />
This is pretty simple, you MUST make a seperate channel for your CHR.  The spam of the primary raid channel makes for too much spam and can cause vital information to be lost in the babble.  Make it a habit of placing this channel in the same number each time.  I place mine as my second channel, the first being the raid channel.  The reason for this is your hotkeys, I have a seperate bank of hotkeys JUST FOR RAIDS, which include /1 and /2 messages for my various heals.  One last thing, keep this channel to as low numbers as possible, meaning the healers, any mainchar botting a healer, and possibly officer(s) if neccissary.<br />
<br />
<br />
ROTATION ORDER / TANK ORDER / OTHER VITAL INFO<br />
Rotation order, rotation timer, tank order, rampage tank order, MGB EE order, ANY other info vital to healing an encounter . . . . . these should be announced in the CHR channel. You MUST know these and HAVE THEM ON HAND.  Some people write this down, my method is to use /note and type all the info into that window to have an on screen, looks something like this . . .<br />
[img noborder]http://home.triad.rr.com/nexuscore/eq/notes.jpg[/img]<br />
Whatever your method, you absolutely must have this info handy, I will be refering to the reasons why throughout this guide.<br />
<br />
<br />
MESSAGE<br />
In order for a CHR to work you HAVE to have a message attatched to your heal.  There are two ways to do this, the first is to have a hotkey with<br />
Line1: HEALMESSAGE<br />
Line2: /castgem 7 (or whatever slot the appropriate heal is in)<br />
the other is to simply have a hotkey with a message bound to the same keyboard key the appropriate heal is, this is the method I prefer as both occur simultaneously as apposed to the small pause the first causes.  The message itself should look something like this . . .<br />
Complete Heal incoming on %t, KEZZ is up next!<br />
Ok, break it down, we have the heal's name, followed by your current target, followed by the next person in the CHR IN ALL CAPS.  Abbreviating the name is fine as long as the message is understood.  NOWHERE in your message should there be a time, the CHR timer WILL change based on under/overestimating the mob, tank going defensive, switching to a lower/higher hp tank.  Adding a timer to your CHR message will only cause confusion DON'T DO IT.  Also, DO NOT USE /pause, its evil, subjective to your proccessor speed, and allows for no flexability midfight.  Finally don't forget to MAKE SURE the message is going to the CHR CHANNEL, you can have it go to multiple channels(though mostely thats just spam) but it ABSOLUTELY has to go in the CHR channel.<br />
<br />
<br />
POSITION<br />
This is vital in almost all the encounters we do today, most of the time doing this right is a simple matter of listening and watching where your fellow healers go.  Three major factors may go into position, there may be others but these are the big ones.<br />
Tank position/range - The tank has to be in range, and often has to be in a specific spot, we have to work this in.<br />
AE Avoidance - On alot of encounters we are able to hide behind pillars, walls, ect in order to avoid the mob's AE thus making sure our heals go off smoothly.<br />
Agro and Rampage - With healing it is EXTREMELY easy to get agro and even easier to be high on the rampage list, it is possible(especially with an ER3 item) to stay in heal range while being out of rampage range.<br />
Bardsong - Often we will have a bard assigned to us for manaregen, on any encounter there may be any number of places you can fulfil the above, but having all of us in pone place helps the collective manaregen.<br />
<br />
<br />
LAY ON HANDS<br />
Often one or more pallies will be assigned to LoH right at the beggining of the fight to avoid us getting agro.  Be aware of this, but mostely this will only be the concern of whoever is initating the CHR.<br />
<br />
<br />
EXECUTION<br />
Ok, you're in the channel, you've got all your vital info on hand, you're in position, now its crunchtime.  The single heaviest duty lies on the person initiating the CHR to make sure it gets up and running at the appropriate time.  The hope is once initiated the CHR will move smoothly, rolling with any changes made on the fly.  Speaking of changes, here is where the vital info comes into play.<br />
Once the CHR starts, COUNT ALONG WITH EVERYONE.  If someone lags more than 1~2secs that could spell disaster, so its your job to take up the slack if the person before you is late(this can be touchy, so make sure you're not jumping the gun, or counting too quick).  The same goes for deaths, they HAVE to be announced ASAP, and EVERYONE has to watch for them, in the main channel as well as the cleric channel.  Stuns, rampage dmg, adds, OoM, deaths . . . all these things will affect someone's ability to complete their heal uninterrupted.  They NEED to be announced and said person will be skipped at least for one round(if it isn't a death).  Obviously we can't have one person micromanaging all this, that is why having all the vital info handy is important, it will be up to YOU to keep track of who's dead, alive, stunned, taking dmg, asked for a skip, OoM, and make your adjustments to the CHR appropriately and smoothly.  Also, we will usually have someone calling out adjustments as much as possible, you will know who they are, if they tell you to do something DO IT.<br />
<br />
<br />
POST KILL<br />
If there are mezzed, kited, or TM'd mobs during the fight make sure you concentrate on healing for these, most notable of these is the Terris Thule encounter where the gargoyles are almost CHR mobs themselves.<br />
Last but not least, make sure there are as few unneccissary death as possible, the biggest factor in this is people dot'd/cursed at the end of the fight, announce in the main channel for people to /tell you with heal/cure requests.  This isn't vital CHR instructions, but general raid stuff for healers.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Thank you for your time, hopefully this will help our raids go more smoothly and efficiently.</font></p>
	
	<p><p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">__________________<br>
